status_message:
So that just happened. Trump won. That's right, Donald J. Trump is president-elect and poised to become the 45th president of the United States.

The people have voted, and we will accept what America decides, but we should not accept that his rhetoric is just "how things are."

Take tonight to grieve. Heck, take the week. President-elect Trump is a scary prospect. But you have the power to keep America strong.

Our country has a system of checks and balances that has survived for 240 years â€” we will survive for four more. This is a really bad time to become cynical or disillusioned or, yes, move to Canada. Your vote in local elections matters now more than ever. Donald Trump cannot get a second term.

Starting tonight and for the next four years, we all must work together to support each other. We must stand against racism, sexism, and oppression and call it out whenever we see it.

Now is the time to reach out and let our neighbors â€” especially those in marginalized communities â€” know we have their backs.

But in all seriousness: Thank you. Thank you to those who have been with us since the beginning, those who just found us, and those of you in between. Without you, we wouldn't be able to do the work that we do here at Upworthy.

See, because of all 10 million of you, we've been able to create stories and videos about nail-painting dads challenging gender norms, celebrities calling out poaching and sexism, members of our communities fighting racism, scientists expanding our minds, and people saving the planet. Plus the stories and videos that make us laugh, that show us the beauty in the world, and that include the occasional cat or two because sometimes the world is strange and weird and in need of cat videos.

We're so lucky to have all of you. We like to say we're all part of the same story â€“ thank you for letting us be a part of yours.

This, of course, comes after other tragedies that have plagued the nation: Newton. Aurora. Virginia Tech. San Bernardino. Fort Hood. And so, so many more. They've had enough â€” and frankly, so has most of the nation.

status_message:
Announcement, everyone! *clears throat* We've reached 8 million fans!

While there isn't a prize for the 8 millionth fan (sorry) or for you early bird trendsetters who have been with us since the very beginning (double sorry), we'd like to take a moment to say thank you. No, really. Thank. YOU.

It's been a great three years. We've told stories about important issues like homelessness, gender inequality, gerrymandering in politics, and climate change.

And you've shared those stories so far and wide that together, we've changed hearts and minds.

We've also shared hilarious comics about parenting, beautiful songs made from the ocean, and videos about small businesses just trying to pay it forward in their communities.

It matters to us that these stories matter to YOU. So thank you from all of us here at Upworthy â€” you're the best. Carry on with your awesome selves!

status_message:
We want to know: What's the best advice your mom ever gave you?

Mother's Day is coming up this Sunday â€” in case you've forgotten, consider this your official reminder! While most of us are scrambling to find the absolute most perfect gift ever for our moms, we wanted to take a minute to celebrate some of the great words of wisdom, life lessons, or advice that's rocked the way we look at the world that our moms have given us over the years. Because let's be honest, moms certainly have a way with words.

So share some of your favorite mom-worthy advice moments with us in the comments, and we might just feature you (and your mom!) in a post of the best responses! Inspirational, funny, cry-worthy, or all around just great, let's hear some of the things your mom has said to you that's deeply affected you or shaped you into the person you are today. We might share some of our favorite responses in a post for Mother's Day!

As some of you may have heard, The Simpsons co-creator Sam Simon passed away today at the age of 59. 

Not only was he partially responsible for one of the most successful animated shows of all time, but he was also a strong advocate for charity and philanthropy, such as The Sam Simon Foundation. In fact, it seems like he decided to leave a good portion of his fortune to charities (if not *all* of it â€” not clear just yet!), which is pretty remarkable if you ask us. 

Sam, you'll be deeply missed.

status_message:
You might not know who Rebecca Lee Crumpler is, but yesterday was a *huge* day in history ... all about her. 

See, on February 24, 1864, she became the first black woman to receive a medical degree in the United States *and* the only black woman to graduate from the New England Female Medical College. 

That's a big deal, y'all, and we're so sad we didn't realize this until a day after the anniversary. So pass it on so others know about her!

If that sounds like you (or a friend!), send an email to casting@upworthy.com with the subject line "Under 30" and include your name, title, and brief explainer (2-3 sentences) about your work and why it's important. Not sure if it's you but maybe it could be? Email us anyway: casting@upworthy.com.
